			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Training points<a name="38197"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 4 04 9:22 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>If you are fear-snaring, put Intimidation on your song macro that your fear song is on.  Remember to take it OFF the macro when you are done.  (You do NOT want to fear a mob by accident, hehe.  Especially an unsnared one!  They go get their friends when you do that.)
<br />

<br />
Why?  Example:  Fear snaring Nezzie in BW for the Epic guts.  The range on the fear song is tiny.  And with wurms, for some reason, you can be INSIDE their freaking bunghole, and still be &quot;too far away&quot; to hit em etc.  Well, the same holds true for your fear song landing.  I do not know the actual range of the Intimidation skill, but I would bet it is slightly better than the fear song.  Also, it serves as a backup in case your fear song is resisted.  Intimidation, from my experience, will land about one out of three times, once maxed.  You can tell which one worked by the messages:
<br />

<br />
Fear song:  Target flees in terror
<br />
Intimidation:  Target looks very afraid
<br />

<br />
To get it trained up, you can also put it on a macro while chant kiting.  You will be too far from the mob for it to actually work, but the skill will still go up.  Again, you must remember to REMOVE it from the macro for regular groups.
<br />

<br />
Another way to train it, if you do not want to risk forgetting to remove it from a macro, is to simply click the button in your action window.  You can do this on corpses, your friends...  It does nothing, of course, except make you look silly, but the skill WILL go up.  
<br />

<br />
Once it is maxed, it is a decent backup for your fear song when fear snaring.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=564823">Scherzo Glissando </a><BR>
Maestro, Molto Espressivo</span></td>
